In typescript, given an array of tokens with the following interface

```
interface Token {
  start: number;
  end: number;
  text: string;
}
```

write a function that can merge any token with the token following it given the array of tokens as an input as well as the index of the token to merge with the token to its right. A merge is defined as: replace the two tokens with a single new token where the `start` is the `start` of the first token, the `end` is the `end` of the second token, and the `text` is the `text` of the first token concatenated with the `text` of the second token.

Sure, here is a function that can merge any token with the token following it given the array of tokens as an input as well as the index of the token to merge with the token to its right. A merge is defined as: replace the two tokens with a single new token where the `start` is the `start` of the first token, the `end` is the `end` of the second token, and the `text` is the `text` of the first token concatenated with the `text` of the second token.

```ts
function mergeTokens(tokens: Token[], index: number): Token[] {
  // Check if the index is out of bounds.
  if (index < 0 || index >= tokens.length) {
    throw new Error(`Index ${index} is out of bounds.`);
  }

  // Get the two tokens to be merged.
  const firstToken = tokens[index];
  const secondToken = tokens[index + 1];

  // Create a new token with the start and end of the first token and the text of the two tokens concatenated.
  const newToken = {
    start: firstToken.start,
    end: secondToken.end,
    text: firstToken.text + secondToken.text,
  };

  // Remove the two tokens to be merged from the array.
  tokens.splice(index, 2);

  // Add the new token to the array.
  tokens.push(newToken);

  return tokens;
}
```

Sure, here is a refactored version of the code that optimizes for readability and does not mutate the tokens array:

```ts
function mergeTokens(tokens: Token[], index: number): Token[] {
  // Check if the index is out of bounds.
  if (index < 0 || index >= tokens.length) {
    throw new Error(`Index ${index} is out of bounds.`);
  }

  // Create a new token with the start and end of the first token and the text of the two tokens concatenated.
  const newToken = {
    start: tokens[index].start,
    end: tokens[index + 1].end,
    text: tokens[index].text + tokens[index + 1].text,
  };

  // Return an array containing the new token and the rest of the tokens.
  return [...tokens.slice(0, index), newToken, ...tokens.slice(index + 2)];
}
```

Here are some comments to help with readability:

* The `if` statement checks if the index is out of bounds. If it is, an error is thrown.
* The `const newToken` statement creates a new token with the start and end of the first token and the text of the two tokens concatenated.
* The `return` statement returns an array containing the new token and the rest of the tokens.
